// GAP #4 (2026-04-19 audit)
// CLAIM: shared struct access inside async function across a yield
//        boundary should error (spec claim: "Lock held across
//        yield/await = deadlock"). Not enforced.
// EFFECT: async function touches shared struct before and after
//         yield. The statement-level lock is acquired at s.v = 1;
//         (released at statement end), yield suspends, next poll
//         re-acquires at s.v = 2;. This doesn't actually deadlock
//         in the per-statement locking model — BUT more complex
//         patterns (e.g., compound expression holding lock across
//         yield) could. The spec was stricter than the
//         implementation needs. May be a spec correction rather
//         than a real compiler fix.
// FIX APPROACH: if the spec intent holds, add AST walker checking
//               that async function bodies don't access shared
//               structs spanning yield boundaries. Medium effort.

shared struct S { u32 v; }
S s;

async void task() {
    s.v = 1;
    yield;
    s.v = 2;
}

u32 main() { return 0; }
